`Array.from` should work. Make sure you are actually grabbing the element containing the text.

You can query on either `.date-duration-duration &gt; div` or simply `.date-duration-duration`.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    // You can use either Array.from or [].slice.call
    var times = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll(&#39;span.date-duration-duration &gt; div&#39;))
      .map(duration =&gt; duration.textContent); // innerHTML will return markup
      
    console.log(times.join(&#39;, &#39;));

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;span class=&quot;date-duration-duration&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;00:00&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;span class=&quot;date-duration-duration&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;06:00&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;span class=&quot;date-duration-duration&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;12:00&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;span class=&quot;date-duration-duration&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;18:00&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

use console.log

    var time = document.querySelectorAll(&#39;.date-duration-duration&#39;);
    var timeArr = Array.from(time);
    for(var i = 0; i &lt; timeArr.length; i++){
        console.log(timeArr[i].innerText);
    }

By default, it logs only last data, incase of timeArr it one data with 15 elements.

You should store your results somewhere. In your example you just call property innerText on elements, without any asignment. For example you can do it this way:

    var time = document.querySelectorAll(&#39;.date-duration-duration&#39;);
    var timeArr = Array.from(time);
    var result = [];

    for(var i = 0; i &lt; timeArr.length; i++){
      result.push(timeArr[i].innerText);
    }

Variable `result` will contain your values as strings. Then you can sum it

    result.reduce((sum, value) =&gt; sum + parseInt(value), 0);

Your code is fine so far. If you `console.log` the expression in your for loop, the code is returning the time for each row:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var time = document.querySelectorAll(&#39;.date-duration-duration&#39;);
    var timeArr = Array.from(time);
    for(var i = 0; i &lt; timeArr.length; i++){
        console.log(timeArr[i].innerText);
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;date-duration-duration&quot;&gt;20:00&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;date-duration-duration&quot;&gt;10:00&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;date-duration-duration&quot;&gt;15:00&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;date-duration-duration&quot;&gt;25:00&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;date-duration-duration&quot;&gt;30:00&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

The next step is to do something with that code. One way to do it is to add the values to an array:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var time = document.querySelectorAll(&#39;.date-duration-duration&#39;);
    var timeArr = Array.from(time);
    var arr = [];
    for(var i = 0; i &lt; timeArr.length; i++){
        arr.push(timeArr[i].innerText);
    }

    console.log(arr);


&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;date-duration-duration&quot;&gt;20:00&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;date-duration-duration&quot;&gt;10:00&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;date-duration-duration&quot;&gt;15:00&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;date-duration-duration&quot;&gt;25:00&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;date-duration-duration&quot;&gt;30:00&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Now you have an array outside of the for loop that you can loop through, add the times together, etc.

